This is a great question, and it gets to the heart of how this specific training tool is designed.

The short answer is: the videos don't currently work because the page is built as a self-contained offline training tool using placeholder links.

Let me explain exactly why and how you can fix it easily.

The Core Reason: Placeholder YouTube Links

Look inside the Media tab's code. You'll find this for the first video:

```html
<iframe src="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dNbjTL21CLY" ...></iframe>
```

This is the key issue. The correct URL to embed a YouTube video looks like this: https://www.youtube.com/embed/dNbjTL21CLY.

The current link is for watching the video on YouTube's website, not for embedding it within your page. The browser doesn't know how to display that inside an iframe.

The 3-Step Fix (Works Immediately)

You don't need to be a coding expert to fix this. Just open the HTML file in a text editor (like Notepad or TextEdit) and make these changes:

Step 1: Find the Media Tab Section
Search for the line that says <!-- ========== MEDIA TAB ========== -->.

Step 2: Replace the YouTube URLs
You will see two lines with iframe src="...". Replace them with the correct URLs.

· Change Video 1 from:
  src="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dNbjTL21CLY"
  To:
  src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/dNbjTL21CLY"
· Change Video 2 from:
  src="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=b_GaUwNPKv8"
  To:
  src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/b_GaUwNPKv8"

Step 3: Save and Refresh
Save the file and refresh the page in your browser. The videos will now play inside the media tab.

A Note on Photos & Offline Use

The weed photos in the "Weed Library" tab are also placeholders. They are looking for local image files in a folder named weeds/ (like weeds/gorse.jpg).

· To add your own: Create a folder named weeds in the same location as this HTML file, and add your photos with the exact names listed in the gallery (e.g., gorse.jpg, ragwort.jpg).
· Offline Use: The rest of the training content (questions, scenarios, quizzes) and your saved progress work completely offline, making it perfect for field use.

Once you make that simple URL change, your videos will work perfectly. The creator used placeholders to keep the file self-contained, but the structure is all there for you to add your own real media.
